I created a dummy webview, and in VS Code 1.95.3 it looks like this: `<activity bar title>: Focus on <webview name> View`

<img width="1493" alt="Screenshot 2024-12-03 at 10 57 22 AM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c01f9b39-b614-46f1-bb5f-9dda14120523">

In VS Code Insiders (1.96) it looks like this: `Focus on <webview name> View`:

<img width="1496" alt="Screenshot 2024-12-03 at 11 01 31 AM" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a1404f0a-be52-42b7-b809-ad54938c8a36">

The activity bar title is missing in VS Code 1.96 insiders version. Repro case below:

`package.json` of the extension:

```json
{
 ... // insert extension name, description, etc...
 "contributes": {
 "viewsContainers": {
 "activitybar": [
 {
 "id": "activitybar",
 "title": "Custom Activity Bar",
 "icon": "insert path to icon image"
 }
 ]
 },
 "views": {
 "activitybar": [
 {
 "type": "webview",
 "id": "customWebview",
 "name": "My Custom Webview"
 }
 ]
 },
```

`extension.ts`:
```js
export class CustomWebview implements WebviewViewProvider {
 // Called when a view first becomes visible.
 public resolveWebviewView(
 webviewView: WebviewView,
 context: WebviewViewResolveContext<unknown>,
 token: CancellationToken,
 ): void | Thenable<void> {
 webviewView.webview.html = `<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
 <title></title>
</head>
<body>
 <p>Hello World!</p>
</body>
</html>`;
 }
}

export async function activate(context: ExtensionContext) {
 context.subscriptions.push(
 window.registerWebviewViewProvider('customWebview', new CustomWebview(), {
 webviewOptions: {
 retainContextWhenHidden: true,
 },
 }),
 );
}
```

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Take the reproducible case shown above and build a .vsix file for the extension
2. Observe that the command is missing the activity bar title in 1.96 Insiders, but in 1.95.3 the command is correct

Note: This was first discovered in https://github.com/microsoft/vscode-discussions/discussions/2420
